{
  "answer": "The phrase 'in propria persona' does not appear anywhere in the corpus. The phrase 'de jure' appears in Charles Comte's Traité de la propriété: VOL I, but only in footnotes as part of bibliographic citations to Grotius's De jure belli ac pacis and Puffendorf's De jure naturæ et gentium — not as Comte's own deployed juridical phrase in prose.\n\nWhat does show through is a broader stratum of French juridical Latin in Comte's footnotes, drawn from the Roman Digest and Justinian's Institutes. Key pinned examples:\n\n1. Ch. 4, fn. 6 (p-75e71b): Comte opens his theory of occupation by citing the Digest directly — *Quod enim nullius est, id ratione naturali occupant; conceditur* (Dig. lib. 4, tit. 1, leg. 3 princ.) — then immediately cites Grotius (*De jure belli ac pacis*, lib. 2, cap. 2, §§ 4–5) and Puffendorf (*De jure naturæ et gentium*, lib. IV, cap. 6). The 'de jure' here is the title-word of those canonical natural-law works, not a standalone adverb.\n\n2. Ch. 4, fn. 7 (p-75e71b): Comte quotes Puffendorf in block Latin — *Ergo proprietas rerum immediatè ex conventione hominum, tacita aut expressa profluxit* — again from De jure naturæ et gentium.\n\n3. Ch. 4, fn. 11: *nullius enim esse creditur* — a bare Roman-law principle used as shorthand for the rule that an island forming in open sea has no owner.\n\n4. Ch. 19, fn. 155–176 (p-fbc67d): Extensive Digest Latin throughout the seashore chapter, e.g. *Maris naturam littora sequuntur ac proindè ad littus maris cuivis accedere licet...* (Dig. lib. I, tit. VII, L. 4) and *Littora in quæ populus romanus imperium habet, populi romani esse arbitror* (Dig. lib. XLIII, tit. VIII, leg. 3).\n\n5. Ch. 19, prose para. p-7d52f5: The one instance where Comte uses a Latin phrase in his own analytical argument rather than a footnote — 'Occupation therefore requires a *de facto* taking of possession, and a durable establishment' — marking the de facto/de jure distinction that was standard in French civil-law training.\n\nIn sum: French juridical Latin shows through Comte's work primarily via dense Roman Digest and Institutes citations in footnotes, plus one in-prose use of de facto (ch. 19). The specific phrase 'in propria persona' is not in the corpus, and 'de jure' appears only inside the titles of cited works rather than as Comte's own prose locution.",
